id="post-1339" class="post-1339 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-body-mind category-good-fact category-health tag-body-mind tag-good-fact tag-health"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/11/23/dont-make-your-bed/" title="Permalink to Don&#8217;t Make Your Bed" rel="bookmark">Don&#8217;t Make Your Bed</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2007/11/23 3:37 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/11/23/dont-make-your-bed/" title="Don&#8217;t Make Your Bed" rel="bookmark">2007/11/23 3:37 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>To protect your health, <a
href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/4181629.stm">it&#8217;s best not to make your bed</a>.</p><blockquote><p>Research suggests that while an unmade bed may look scruffy it is also unappealing to house dust mites thought to cause asthma and other allergies.</p><p>A Kingston University study discovered the bugs cannot survive in the warm, dry conditions found in an unmade bed.</p><p>The average bed could be home to up to 1.5 million house dust mites.</p></blockquote><div
